nd they decrease government dependency, undermining the patronage strategies underpinning authoritarianism.The authors discuss how international migration produces a decentralized flow of income that generally circumvents governments to reach citizens who act as democratizing agents. Documenting why dictatorships fall and how this process has changed in the last three decades, the authors show that remittances increase the likelihood of protest and reduce electoral support for authoritarian incumbents. Combining global macroanalysis with microdata and case studies of Senegal and Cambodia, the book demonstrates how remittances foster democracy.Migration and Democracy demonstrates how the movement of people from authoritarian nations to higher-income countries can enhance democratic expansion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocratizationxEconomic aspects. 0aDictatorship. 0aEmigrant remittancesxPolitical aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxEconomic aspects. 0aEmigration and immigrationxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Immigration.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAdventurism.  aAnt Financial Services Group.  aAntipathy.  aBeneficiary.  aCentrism.  aCitizens (Spanish political party).  aClientelism.  aCollective behavior.  aConsumption (economics).  aCronyism.  aDemocracy promotion.  aDemocratic consolidation.  aDemocratization.  aDeveloped country.  aDevelopment aid.  aDictatorship.  aEconomic liberalization.  aEffectiveness.  aElectoral reform.  aEstimation.  aExplanation.  aFactors of production.  aFamily income.  aGovernment of China.  aGovernment shutdown in the United States.  aGovernment spending.  aHuman capital flight.  aIllegal immigration.  aImport.  aIncome.  aIncumbent.  aInsurgency.  aInternational non-governme